<div id="comment_status_64430494" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64430494" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64430494" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64430494" name="comment_link_64430494" href="//tech.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23304996&amp;cid=64430494" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64430494)" >Re:immaterial</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64430494" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64430494); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>5</a>, Informative)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~Anubis+IV">Anubis IV</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~Anubis+IV">( 1279820 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64430494">		
		on Sunday April 28, 2024 @02:57AM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//tech.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23304996&amp;cid=64430494">#64430494</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64430494"><p>I fail to see how this is ignoring the Constitution. People are calling this a &ldquo;ban&rdquo;, but legally speaking it isn&rsquo;t. TikTok itself is fine: it&rsquo;s the foreign ownership of TikTok that&rsquo;s at stake, and yes, that distinction matters. We can&rsquo;t do business with, say, Iran or Libya because Congress has the Constitutional authority to regulate commerce with foreign entities, as they should, and all they&rsquo;re saying here is that TikTok has to change hands from its current, foreign owner. That&rsquo;s well within their Constitutional authority. If TikTok gets a new owner, it&rsquo;s fine to continue.</p><p>It&rsquo;s absurd to think that any company would be able to wrap illegal commercial activity in a robe of free speech and then try to argue that they&rsquo;re untouchable as a result. If that were permissible, we&rsquo;d be able to legally perjure ourselves, engage in defamation, or commit fraud. Free speech has always had limits (e.g. the First Amendment uses the definite article&mdash;<b>the</b> freedom of speech&mdash;to refer to an idea that would have been understood in the context of existing case law and precedent, rather than a generic, limitless idea), hence why the more absolutist notion of it you see spreading in some echo chambers these days was called &ldquo;absurd&rdquo; when it was raised before the Supreme Court a few decades back.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64430494">
<span class="ind"></span><a id="reply_link_64430494" class="btn link" href="//tech.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23304996&amp;op=Reply&amp;threshold=1&amp;commentsort=0&amp;mode=thread&amp;pid=64430494" onclick="D2.replyTo(64430494); return false;">Reply to This</a> <span class="ind"></span><a class="btn link" href="//tech.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23304996&amp;threshold=1&amp;commentsort=0&amp;mode=thread&amp;cid=64430340" onclick="return D2.selectParent(64430340)">Parent</a> 	<a href="#" class="comment_share_toggle btn link">Share</a>
